 between the verbal performance of rhetoric and other performative modes in generating, sustaining, and transmitting a persuasive form of religiosity. The essays in this book cover a wide chronological range (from the first century to late antiquity) and diverse topical examples contribute to the collection’s thematic centre: the relations among formalized and technical verbal performances (rhetoric, texts) and other forms of persuasive performances (ritual, practices), the social agendas that early Christians pursued by means of verbal, rhetorical performances, and the larger social context in which Christians and other religious groups competitively jockeyed to attract the minds and bodies of audiences in the Greco-Roman world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch historyxPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aPersasion (Rhétorique)xAspects religieuxxChristianisme. 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric)xReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory. 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric)xSocial aspectsxMediterranean Region. 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric)xSocial aspectszMediterranean Region. 0aPersuasion (Rhétorique)xAspect socialxMéditerranée, Région de la. 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 0aRhétorique ancienne. 0aÉglisexHistoirexca 30-600 (Église primitive). 4aHistory: Jewish Studies. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh1 aArnal, William E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraun, Willi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraun, Willi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDe Bruyn, Theodore S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurst, Laurence Broad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKile, Chad, econtribut